Visible->True,
TaggingRules->{
 "ModificationHighlight" -> False, "ColorType" -> "", "LinkTrails" -> "", 
  "ExampleCounter" -> 1, 
  "Openers" -> {
   "PrimaryExamplesSection" -> Open, "ExampleSection" -> {"0" -> Open}}, 
  "NewStyles" -> True, "CitationPopupData" -> {"2021", ""}, "ShowCitation" -> 
  False, "RootCaptions" -> "", "HeaderCoreAreaLink" -> {}, 
  "Metadata" -> {
   "built" -> "{2026, 4, 12, 18, 0, 1.413779}", 
    "history" -> {"13", "", "", ""}, "context" -> "QuantumMob`Q3`", 
    "keywords" -> {"hidden subgroup problems"}, "specialkeywords" -> {}, 
    "tutorialcollectionlinks" -> {}, "index" -> True, "label" -> 
    "Quantum Mob/ Q3 Tech Note", "language" -> "en", "paclet" -> 
    "QuantumMob/Q3", "status" -> "None", "summary" -> 
    "Let f:{0,1}^m\\[RightArrow]{0,1}^n be a periodic function, and \
f(x+\\[Lambda])=f(x) for all x and fixed \\[Lambda]. The period-finding \
problem is to find the unknown (primary) period \\[Lambda] with the least \
queries to the function f. For simplicity, we assume that \\[Lambda] is a \
divider of 2^m. As long as an efficient implementation of the quantum oracle \
corresponding to function f, U_f:TemplateBox[{x}, \
Ket]\\[CircleTimes]TemplateBox[{y}, Ket]\\[RightTeeArrow]TemplateBox[{x}, \
Ket]\\[CircleTimes]TemplateBox[{RowBox[{y, \\[CirclePlus], RowBox[{f, (, x, \
)}]}]}, Ket], is available, one can construct an efficient quantum algorithm \
to find period \\[Lambda] of function f.", "synonyms" -> {}, 
    "tabletags" -> {}, "title" -> "The Period-Finding Algorithm", 
    "titlemodifier" -> "", "metadescription" -> "", "windowtitle" -> 
    "The Period-Finding Algorithm", "type" -> "Tech Note", "uri" -> 
    "QuantumMob/Q3/tutorial/PeriodFindingAlgorithm"}},
